Introduction
Git is a distributed version control system that helps you track changes in your codebase. Whether you're working on a solo project or collaborating with a team, understanding Git commands is essential for effective version control.

Installation
Before using Git, ensure it is installed on your system. You can download it from the official Git website.

Configuration
Configure your Git environment with your name and email:

bash

git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "your.email@example.com"
Basic Commands
Initialize a Repository:

bash
git init
Check Repository Status:

bash
git status
Add Changes to Staging Area:

bash
git add <file>
Commit Changes:

bash
git commit -m "Your commit message"
